post_text:
4th and 5th grade students have been studying buoyancy and relative density in science.
4th grade students used various craft materials to construct a floating boat that could support a load of at least 50 grams without sinking.
5th grade students had to design and build a structure that would float while holding as many pennies as possible, using only foil, 10 drinking straws, 20 grams of modeling clay and 60 cm of masking tape.
Student enjoyed building and testing their designs.

post_text: Just make a mark and see where it takes you! Kindergarten is studying the book The Dot by Peter H. Reynolds. Today they participated in International Dot Day! They dressed in dots, created art with dots, did addition with dots, and even ate dots for snack! Most importantly they learned that they can take chances, be brave, be helpful, be artistic and be creative all by starting with a small, but powerful DOT!

post_text:
Last night at the Board Meeting we recognized Kami Nunn and Sophie Guerrero as our students of the month. We were honored to have them lead us in our pledges. Their teachers had the following to say about their nominations:

Kami has been selected as Student of the Month by her teachers because of her positive attitude. We can count on Kami to come to class with a smile and be prepared to learn. She is willing to help a fellow classmate or a teacher when needed. We appreciate her pleasant attitude towards classmates and adults. Kami has shown the Antelope way by working hard, dreaming big, and being kind! She is a pleasure to have in class.

Sophie is another student that has been seen showing the Antelope way. She works hard in all of her classes, she's kind to everyone she sees and has big dreams to be successful. Sophie is a pleasure to work with in class. We appreciate her out of the box thinking and her positive attitude!

Please join us in congratulating our Students of the Month!

WHAT? WHAT? Paul Q. was recognized today with a WHAT? WHAT? card from Mrs. Phillips.

Staff at Whiteface Elementary are recognizing students with WHAT? WHAT? cards for going over and beyond in their behaviors or academics. Paul was celebrated in his classroom as well as in the office with staff giving high-fives and showing off their best happy dance moves.
If a student receives a WHAT?WHAT? card, they get to call a parent and explain what they did to deserve this extra praise. The student then will have his/her picture taken and posted on FB and on our WHAT? WHAT? board for everyone to see and celebrate!
We are super proud of Paul for earning the first WHAT?WHAT? card!

post_text:
Our first home game is Thursday 8/27 vs Petersburg. Our JV will play here starting at 6pm. We are excited to have our first game and look forward to seeing everyone in attendance.
Self-Screening: According to TEA/UIL all Students, Staff, and Visitors must self-screen. Prior to attending school, any school function, or coming to campus; students, staff, and visitors must self-screen for any of the symptoms of possible COVID-19 or known close contact with a person who is lab confirmed to have COVID-19 (if exposure to the active confirmed case occurred within the last 14 days). If you have any of these signs, symptoms or meet the criteria, please email: inform@whitefaceschool.net You will be not allowed to be at the school function and we will reach out to you to see how we can help!

As always, if you need anything from us, please do not hesitate to ask!

post_text: Last night at the Board Meeting we recognized Audra Davis for her participation in the Texas Lesson Study. The TLS is a job embedded professional development process that is designed to improve teacher effectiveness and increase self-mastery. In the study, Audra was able to build collaborative relationships, improve school culture, and enhance; pedagogical skills, content knowledge, motivation, and capacity to predict and observe student thinking. WCISD would like to thank Mrs. Davis for being an integral part of our #WCISDFAMILY and for continually going above and beyond for our students!

post_text:
As school is right around the corner and more people are coming to school, we need to make a quick announcement about self-screening.
Self-Screening: According to TEA all Students, Staff, and Visitors must self-screen. Prior to attending school, any school function, or coming to campus; students, staff, and visitors must self-screen for any of the symptoms of possible COVID-19 or known close contact with a person who is lab confirmed to have COVID-19 (if exposure to the active confirmed case occurred within the last 14 days). If you have any of these signs, symptoms, or meet the criteria please email: inform@whitefaceschool.net You will be not allowed to be at the school function and we will reach out to you to see how we can help!
With that out of the way, we are ECSTATIC to be back to school. Staff are happily jumping through all of the new hoops TEA has made to ‚Äúcome back to school‚Äù because we are so excited to see you all!
As always, if you need anything from us, please do not hesitate to ask!

Hello Antelope Fans!!

CALLING ALL ANTELOPE BAND MEMBERS!!

Summer band is kicking off this week with 5 rookie rehearsals.
A rookie is anyone who did not march a contest spot last season. These are all incoming 8th graders plue the A Rank (alternates) from last year. If you got a paper copy of the letter in the mail, you are a rookie and we are expecting you on Monday night, August 3rd at 7:00 pm!

Full band will begin rehearsals on Monday, August 17th at 7:00 pm!

ANY band member who wants a fundamental review or is able to help our rookies, can come to the first five rehearsals. Upper classmen, show your leadership!!

Please see the attachments for more details. Make note that the fall schedule has some changes.

Thank you for your flexibility as we deal with these usual times!!

See you soon!!

Mrs. Brazil and Mrs. Scoggins

P.S. Don't forget to get your physical if you have not done so already!!

THANK YOU FOR SUPPORTING OUR ANTELOPES!!

WCISD BACK TO SCHOOL PLAN 2020-2021 is here in 2 easy steps!
Whiteface CISD plans to provide face-to-face instruction beginning on August 19, 2020. Remote instruction option will also be available.

Step 1: Please click on the link to access the details of the plan: http://www.whitefaceschool.net/UserFiles/Servers/Server_327320/File/1%20nwheeler/Whiteface%20CISD%20newsletter%207%2030%202020%20Update%202.pdf

Step 2: All parents will be required to register each student for either remote or in-person instruction through the online application by Friday, August 7, 2020. Parents will be asked to make a firm commitment in order for Whiteface CISD to staff accordingly. Parents please use the following link to register: https://forms.gle/HYTPsqSDPsBewKAB6

Please Note: The remote instruction option will not be the same type of instruction provided during the spring school closure. The requirements for remote instruction are significantly more demanding on student‚Äôs daily participation and completion of work at home, as compared to this past spring.

TEA has made additional revisions to the start of school plan. We all know they will revise this plan quite a few times prior to the start of school. NOTHING is set in stone yet.

WCISD is going to wait until late July/early August to make a definitive school start plan. That being said, we are requesting YOUR input into our plan. If you have not already done so PLEASE respond to the survey:

https://forms.gle/T5k5FCfEoQ8zFoJi8

As a note (as it sets today): WCISD will offer face-to-face and remote instruction. The remote instruction is a mixture of the synchronous plan and the asynchronous plan, however in order for more leniency (for attendance purposes and for student growth) we are labeling it as the "asynchronous plan." In other words: the remote instruction plan will include timelines, daily activities, and possibly some "live" aspects.

As always if you have any questions please do not hesitate to ask!

post_text:
Whiteface middle school students were named State winners, Regional winners, AND National finalists in the 17th annual eCybermission STEM competition, awarding $14,000 to these students for their work this year!

The Whiteface/Whitharral 6th grade team ‚ÄúRecess Guardians‚Äù was named 2nd place Texas state winner for eCYBERMISSION. Recess Guardians project was awarded with each student receiving a $500 U.S. savings bond. The team includes Briella Davis, Whiteface Middle School, Reegan Couch, Whiteface Middle School, Miley Hodge, Whiteface Middle School and Ayden Dockery, Whitharral Middle School. Led by Team Advisor Katherine Kucel, teacher for Whiteface CISD, the Recess Guardians project focused on helping defend schools or parks during an outside shooter situation. ‚ÄúOver 4,000 projects were submitted this year and it is an honor for our Cochran & Hockley county students to take the top spots in the state! We are so proud of their accomplishments,‚Äù stated Kucel.

Please join us in congratulating yet another outstanding achievement from the #WCISDFAMILY

Adam S Cline is with Misael Castaneda.
May 15 at 8:43 PM ¬∑

Most Outstanding Powerlifter

Misael worked hard at his craft and it paid off in a big way this year. He ended last season with a total of 1085 pounds. We entered the season with a goal of 1200 lbs. We had to reset that goal early as Misael was passed it after the first meet. He improved every time out and we ended the season with a total 1315 pounds and a berth in the regional powerlifting meet. Hard work pays off! We look forward to an exciting and rewarding 2021 lifting season!

According to TEA: Prior to attending any ceremony or event, participating students and attending family members must be screened (via questioning) for any of the following new or worsening signs or symptoms of possible COVID-19:
‚Ä¢ Cough,
‚Ä¢ Shortness of breath or difficulty breathing,
‚Ä¢ Chills,
‚Ä¢ Repeated shaking with chills,
‚Ä¢ Muscle pain,
‚Ä¢ Headache,
‚Ä¢ Sore throat,
‚Ä¢ Loss of taste or smell,
‚Ä¢ Diarrhea,
‚Ä¢ Feeling feverish or a measured temperature greater than or equal to 100.0 degrees Fahrenheit,
‚Ä¢ Known close contact with a person who is lab confirmed to have COVID-19 if exposure to the active confirmed case occurred within the last 14 days.

If you have any of these signs or symptoms please email: inform@whitefaceschool.net and You WILL BE EXCLUDED from the activity.

Thank you all for your understanding during these times.

post_text:
Hello Antelope Fans!!

Today's Senior Spotlight is:

Carson Rice

Carson will be an Honor Graduate this year.

Her future plans are: Travel around the world to help people and animals.

Her favorite teachers are: Coach Gruhlkey, Coach Rocha, Mr. Ladd

Her favorite high school memory: Going to watch the blue man group. We all got to go out together for a few hours and have fun. It was the first time in the whole year I got to forget every worry on my mind and just relax, have fun, and be able to yell in a building without being told to be quiet :)

Her advice for next year's seniors: Treat your classmates like a family. You never know when something might happen where you never get to see them again. Then you get to live with every regret you have because you didn't appreciate them when you had the chance. High school isn't everything, plan ahead. Live a good life every day you can. Make the most of the time you get with the people you have to see every day whether you like them or not. Try to understand them and be there for them.

THANK YOU FOR SUPPORTING OUR ANTELOPES!!

TRANSFER STUDENTS (PARENTS) PLEASE READ!!

As you know, every year, every transfer student MUST RESUBMIT a transfer application. These applications on online on our website. PLEASE submit the correct one.

Hello Antelope Fans!!

PARENTS!! Whiteface CISD will be having our Whiteface students' PERSONAL BELONGING PICK UP TOMORROW FROM 9:00 am to 4:00 pm.

The ELEMENTARY students will pick up their belongings under the awning where they normally pick up packets. Teachers will be waiting for you so we can get all your things to you!

PLEASE BE PATIENT!! We will try to mitigate this process the best we can!!

The SECONDARY students will pick up their belongings at the Band Hall. We will allow students to come in (a few at a time) and retrieve their belongings as quickly as possible.

PLEASE UNDERSTAND, we bagged all personal belongings solely from the locker it came from. If you find something in your bag that belongs to someone else, you may leave it with us to get it to the right person. We will have staff to help facilitate this as well.

The time of pick up is to allow flexibility, PLEASE KNOW that you may come during the regular lunch time to prevent multiple trips into Whiteface, although we would LOVE TO SEE YOU!!

THANK YOU FOR SUPPORTING OUR ANTELOPES!!

Hello Antelope Fans!!

Today's Senior Spotlight is:

Elijah Samarron

Eli will be an Honor Graduate this year.

He plans on going into the workforce working as a carpenter.

His favorite teachers are: Mr. Brazil and Mr. Clark

His favorite high school memory: I have had a lot of fun at Whiteface and have many memories that will stay with me through the years. My favorite high school memory would have to be during basketball season when me and Sam Hodge would be spectators/managers. Always laughing and having a good time.

His advice for next year's seniors: Choose something you have a passion for and strive to go higher. Be your own path taker and don't change your mind because people disagree with your choice of career or college or the way you dress. There are leaders and followers so pick which one you would want to be.

THANK YOU FOR SUPPORTING OUR SENIOR ANTELOPES!!

post_text:
Hello Antelope Fans!!

Today's Senior Spotlight is:

Audrey Ayers

Audrey will be an Honor Graduate this year.

She plans to attend the University of Ole Miss to study Biology.

Her favorite teachers are: Coach Simmons and Mr. Clark. She says that both of these men have been there through the good, the bad and the ugly and I will be forever grateful for them.

Her favorite high school memories are all the road trips to basketball camps in the summer.

Her advice for next year's seniors:
Take every moment in your senior year, don't rush anything because you will blink and you will be done with high school. I promise that you will want it to be over but I promise it is coming and when it is here you will not get those moments back. Make memories, have fun, run those extra sprints, never give up, and live your last year of high school because before you know it you will be a "has been".
THANK YOU FOR SUPPORTING OUR SENIOR ANTELOPES!!

Due to COVID-19, WCISD is admittedly hard to get a hold of right now. With that in mind, we wanted to give you a few options to get a hold of us. If you need anything at all in this time, please know we are here for you and we will help as much as we can!

Contact Information:

Joel Dietz, Technology Director: jdietz@whitefaceschool.net or 806 370 0073

Scott Lucas, Elementary Principal: slucas@whitefaceschool.net

Chris Mendez, Secondary Principal: cmendez@whitefaceschool.net

Nate Wheeler, Superintendent: nwheeler@whitefaceschool.net

Note: While our normal communication turnaround time is usually 24hours, we may be slower than that at the current so please continue to be patient with us. Thanks for everything you do!

We WILL get through this, We WILL be stronger because of it, and we WILL do it all because we are the #WCISDFAMILY

post_text:
Instructional Material Pick Up - Monday March 30th

Pick up for instructional materials will be held on Monday, March 30th for all Whiteface students.

Students living in-district will pick up their materials from 11:30am -12:30pm and can then move through the food services line to pick up their meals.

Transfer students may pick up their materials from 1:00-3:00 pm.

This will be a drive-through process and everyone should enter through the car line entrance in front of the Elementary.

All materials and devices will be delivered to your car. District staff will guide each vehicle through the line and process. Parents/students should not leave their cars and will not be allowed to enter the building.

In an effort to expedite delivery, technology devices will only be checked out to families who were pre-identified by the District survey and have received an email from the IT Department. (Emails will go out today, Friday 3/27/20).

As always we appreciate your understanding and patience during these times.

‚òòÔ∏è ‚òòÔ∏è Leprechaun Trap
Kindergarten Style ‚òòÔ∏è ‚òòÔ∏è

All week long we kept seeing signs that a leprechaun might be in our classroom, so we made a plan to catch them! We gathered our supplies, and worked as a team to build a trap! Since the leprechauns made messes each time we left the room we locked our room up tight, and secured the door with lots of tape before we went to lunch. Our hope was that the leprechauns couldn‚Äôt get in to make a mess, but just in case we knew we could lure them
into our trap with all things shiny and green! (and rainbow of course) We came back to find those mischievous little rascals had made an awful mess! We didn‚Äôt get the gold, but they did leave us snacks and a pot of goodies!

Hello Antelope Fans!!

Our Antelopes continue to RISE!!

Our Whiteface Band brought home straight 1s Thursday from UIL Concert/Sightreading Contest.

Combined with our Division I marching season in the fall, this means our school again has one of the few SWEEPSTAKES band programs in the state of Texas.

A special shout out to this group of Seniors who has stuck with the program all the way to the finish. Such dedication and leadership is a big contributor to the longstanding success of the Whiteface Band!

CONGRATULATIONS to Mrs. Scoggins and Mrs. Brazil for your dedication and your never ending support for our students!! You are truly appreciated!!

THANK YOU FOR SUPPORTING OUR ANTELOPES!!

post_text:
For 121 days we have learned! At the end of the week energy had to be burned!

A Seusstastical party was in store! From the Kindergarten room there were a lot of roars!

With green Oobleck dripping, and stories galore we even read books laying in 121 balloons on the floor!

Counting, graphing, and addition too; there were so many fun things to do!

We met characters from the books we have read, and Jaxon wore an elephant on his head!

To top it all off a feast was had! Green Eggs and ham! Would it be good or bad?

Humming fish,truffula seeds, pork and eggs chartreuse were all washed down with a glass of Seuss Juice!

After tummies were filled, there was one more big hit!!! Our 121 second balloon party was legit!!!

post_text:
Can you say, ‚ÄúI love my heart‚Äù?

February 7-14th is the National Heart Awareness week. During the week, attention is brought to leading causes of heart disease, statistics, and congenital heart defects. Every mother should have her unborn/newborn baby screened for a CHD. 1 in 100 are born every day with a form of heart defect. Whiteface Elementary is supporting CHD angels and warriors by wearing red today, (or a lovely shade of pink).

Remember to Be An Andersen, who is a CHD angel.

At 5:30 this morning there was no snow and the roads were fine, but surrounding communities were reporting some isolated slick spots. Therefore the decision was made to delay school. Then as we began to prepare for school it started to snow. That's West Texas for you, we could have griped and complained but we didn't. Employees such as Mr. Lucas simply picked up a shovel and got to work! Mr. Scoggins blew off the snow and Mr. Perez shoveled as well! Thank you and everyone else that simply made it work today!

Thanks to Mr. Lucas for not only being a faithful greeter come rain or shine, but also being the sidewalk shoveler today!

post_text:
As "bad weather season" is on our horizon, maybe as early as today around noon, I wanted to be sure everyone is on the same page as to our plan. We have a decent chance for snow today (2/4) through tomorrow (2/5). We will be extra vigilant during this time to ensure we are ALL safe. If you do not hear anything from us, then "No news is good news" come on in during regular time and we will see you when you get here.
I want to be VERY clear: If you EVER feel like it is unsafe to drive, walk, bike, skate, scoot, or otherwise commute to work; PLEASE STAY SAFE, STAY HOME, DRIVE SLOW, whatever it takes to be safe. Let us know so we can handle your absence/tardiness, but ABOVE ALL ELSE STAY SAFE!
As the weather progresses we will be updating through the call out system, facebook, local news, and email.

As the weather progresses we will be updating through the call out system, facebook, local news, and email.

post_text: 2nd and 1st grade celebrated 100 days brighter today! Each student counted out 100 items at home and brought them to school to use in stations. First we learned to group them in several different ways making skip counting fun! Then we learned about the origins of currency and the barter system. They found out real quick not all items were worth the same amount to everyone! And Mrs. Couch holds a taxation on all goods in her classroom. Her favorite is starburst ;) Ask your students about quartering out a hundred and how to skip count by 25s.

Misael Castanada had a great day in the gym!! He improved 65 pounds from two weeks ago for a total weight of 1210. He had 300# pushed and locked out on bench press, but the spotter racked the weight before the judge call for rack, and he had to try again. He didn‚Äôt have much rest before he tried again and fell short. Still had 2 PR‚Äôs in bench and dead lift. Finishing 4th for the day.
Kaden Coats also did great!!! This was Kaden‚Äôs first ever power lifting meet. He got bumped into a heavier weight class. Kaden also had 2 PR‚Äôs today in bench and squats.
Jose Borunda did AWESOME today!!! This was also his first power lifting meet. He medaled with a third place finish. He had 3 PR‚Äôs in squat, bench, and deadlift!!!
These young men greatly represented Whiteface today. Not only in strength but in character and integrity!! We are so proud of our Antelopes!
